---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import Sidebar from '../../components/Sidebar.astro';
const title = "Environmental Quenching - ArXiv Atlas";

import WikiLink from '../../components/WikiLink.astro';
---
<Base title={title}>
  <Sidebar />
  <main class="page-main">
    <h1 class="page-title">Environmental Quenching</h1>
    
    <div class="disambiguation">
      Not to be confused with <WikiLink slug="pages/mass_quenching" text="Mass Quenching" /> or <WikiLink slug="pages/morphological_quenching" text="Morphological Quenching" />, which are internally-driven processes.
    </div>

    <div class="infobox">
      <h3 class="infobox-title">Environmental Quenching</h3>
      <table>
        <tr>
          <th>Type:</th>
          <td>Quenching mechanism (external)</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Environments:</th>
          <td><WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_clusters" text="Galaxy Clusters" />, <WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_groups" text="Galaxy Groups" /></td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Key Mechanisms:</th>
          <td>
            <WikiLink slug="pages/ram_pressure_stripping" text="Ram Pressure Stripping" /><br>
            <WikiLink slug="pages/strangulation" text="Strangulation" /><br>
            <WikiLink slug="pages/preprocessing" text="Preprocessing" /><br>
            Tidal stripping
          </td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Timescales:</th>
          <td>1-8 Gyr depending on mechanism</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <th>Key Diagnostic:</th>
          <td><WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_infall_time" text="Infall time" /> via <WikiLink slug="pages/projected_phase_space" text="projected phase space" /></td>
        </tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <p>
      <strong>Environmental quenching</strong> refers to the suppression or cessation of <WikiLink slug="pages/star_formation" text="star formation" /> in galaxies due to processes associated with their local environment, particularly in <WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_clusters" text="galaxy clusters" /> and <WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_groups" text="groups" />. Unlike internal quenching mechanisms (<WikiLink slug="pages/morphological_quenching" text="morphological quenching" />, <WikiLink slug="pages/agn_feedback" text="AGN feedback" />), environmental quenching acts on galaxies through external interactions with the hot intracluster/intragroup medium and with other satellites<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref2">2</a></sup>.
    </p>
    <p>
      The effectiveness of environmental quenching depends critically on how long a galaxy has been a satellite of its host - the <WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_infall_time" text="infall time" />, T<sub>inf</sub>. As galaxies become satellites, their properties evolve from field-like to showing signatures of environmental processing on timescales that depend on T<sub>inf</sub><sup><a href="#ref3">3</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref4">4</a></sup>.
    </p>

    <h2 id="section-0">Physical Mechanisms</h2>

    <h3>Ram Pressure Stripping</h3>
    <p><WikiLink slug="pages/ram_pressure_stripping" text="Ram pressure stripping" /> removes gas directly from a satellite galaxy as it moves through the hot intracluster medium. This can rapidly quench star formation by removing the fuel supply. Evidence suggests this process operates even beyond R<sub>200</sub><sup><a href="#ref5">5</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref6">6</a></sup>.</p>

    <h3>Strangulation (Starvation)</h3>
    <p><WikiLink slug="pages/strangulation" text="Strangulation" /> cuts off the supply of fresh gas from the cosmic web to the galaxy's halo, causing star formation to decline as existing gas reserves are consumed. This operates on longer timescales (several Gyr) than ram pressure stripping.</p>

    <h3>Preprocessing</h3>
    <p><WikiLink slug="pages/preprocessing" text="Preprocessing" /> refers to environmental effects that occur before a galaxy reaches the main cluster, for example in group-scale halos or at large cluster-centric radii (beyond R<sub>200</sub>). Haines et al. (2015)<sup><a href="#ref6">6</a></sup> demonstrated the need for preprocessing to explain quenching patterns in LoCuSS clusters.</p>

    <h3>Tidal Interactions</h3>
    <p>Gravitational tidal forces from the host halo and from galaxy-galaxy interactions can strip stars and gas from satellite galaxies, altering their morphology and suppressing star formation.</p>

    <h2 id="section-1">Infall Time as a Clock</h2>
    
    <p>The <WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_infall_time" text="infall time" /> T<sub>inf</sub> serves as a clock for environmental processing. Estimating T<sub>inf</sub> from <WikiLink slug="pages/projected_phase_space" text="projected phase space" /> allows observers to link satellite galaxy properties to environmental exposure duration<sup><a href="#ref3">3</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref7">7</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref8">8</a></sup>.</p>
    <p><WikiLink slug="pages/masson_2026_infall_time_pps" text="Masson & Parker (2026)" /><sup><a href="#ref3">3</a></sup> provide the latest continuous calibration of T<sub>inf</sub> as a function of projected phase-space position and stellar mass, valid for 0 &lt; z &lt; 1. Key finding: the T<sub>inf</sub> distribution at a given PPS location is often bimodal (early vs. late infallers), meaning environmental exposure histories are more complex than a single timescale can capture.</p>

    <h2 id="section-2">Observational Evidence</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Boselli & Gavazzi (2006)<sup><a href="#ref1">1</a></sup> provided a comprehensive review of environmental effects on late-type galaxies in nearby clusters.</li>
      <li>Wetzel et al. (2013)<sup><a href="#ref2">2</a></sup> quantified satellite quenching timescales as a function of stellar mass.</li>
      <li>Kim et al. (2023)<sup><a href="#ref9">9</a></sup> found a gradual decline of star formation since cluster infall at 0.3 &lt; z &lt; 1.1, using PPS-based kinematic estimates.</li>
      <li>Oxland et al. (2024)<sup><a href="#ref10">10</a></sup> and Sampaio et al. (2021)<sup><a href="#ref11">11</a></sup> applied simulation-calibrated T<sub>inf</sub> to study quenching in observed samples.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="section-3">Connection to Galaxy Bimodality</h2>
    <p>Environmental quenching is one of the key mechanisms driving the <WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_bimodality" text="galaxy bimodality" /> - the division of galaxies into star-forming (<WikiLink slug="pages/blue_cloud" text="blue cloud" />) and quiescent (<WikiLink slug="pages/red_sequence" text="red sequence" />) populations. In cluster environments, environmental quenching operates on Gyr timescales, providing evidence for slow transitions through the <WikiLink slug="pages/green_valley" text="green valley" /><sup><a href="#ref2">2</a></sup>.</p>

    <h2 id="section-4">Open Questions</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>What is the relative importance of ram pressure stripping vs. strangulation vs. preprocessing as a function of halo mass and redshift?</li>
      <li>How do bimodal infall-time distributions affect our interpretation of satellite quenching timescales?<sup><a href="#ref3">3</a></sup></li>
      <li>At what cluster-centric radius do environmental effects first become significant?<sup><a href="#ref5">5</a></sup><sup><a href="#ref6">6</a></sup></li>
      <li>How does environmental quenching interact with internal quenching mechanisms?</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 id="section-5">See Also</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_infall_time" text="Galaxy Infall Time" /> - The key timescale for environmental processing</li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/projected_phase_space" text="Projected Phase Space" /> - Diagnostic for inferring environmental histories</li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/morphological_quenching" text="Morphological Quenching" /> - Internal quenching mechanism</li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/galaxy_bimodality" text="Galaxy Bimodality" /> - Broader observational context</li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/masson_2026_infall_time_pps" text="Masson & Parker (2026)" /> - Latest T<sub>inf</sub> calibration</li>
      <li><WikiLink slug="pages/portal_galaxy_evolution" text="Portal: Galaxy Evolution" /></li>
    </ul>

    <div class="references">
      <h2>References</h2>
      <ol>
        <li id="ref1">Boselli, A., Gavazzi, G. (2006). "Environmental effects on late-type galaxies in nearby clusters." <em>PASP</em> 118, 517-559.</li>
        <li id="ref2">Wetzel, A. R., et al. (2013). Galaxy quenching in groups and clusters.</li>
        <li id="ref3">Masson, F., Parker, L. C. (2026). "Calibrating Galaxy Infall Times in Groups and Clusters with IllustrisTNG Simulations." <em>ApJ</em> (accepted). <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2603.13010">arXiv:2603.13010</a>.</li>
        <li id="ref4">Weinmann, S. M., et al. (2009). Environmental dependence of satellite galaxy properties.</li>
        <li id="ref5">Balogh, M. L., Navarro, J. F., Morris, S. L. (2000). "The origin of star formation gradients in rich galaxy clusters." <em>ApJ</em> 540, 113-121.</li>
        <li id="ref6">Haines, C. P., et al. (2015). "LoCuSS: the slow quenching of star formation in cluster galaxies and the need for pre-processing." <em>ApJ</em> 806, 101.</li>
        <li id="ref7">Pasquali, A., et al. (2019). Projected phase space zones and mean infall times.</li>
        <li id="ref8">Rhee, J., et al. (2017). Phase-space analysis of cluster satellites.</li>
        <li id="ref9">Kim, K. J., et al. (2023). "A gradual decline of star formation since cluster infall." <em>ApJ</em> 955, 32.</li>
        <li id="ref10">Oxland, M., et al. (2024). Environmental processing of cluster satellites.</li>
        <li id="ref11">Sampaio, V. M., et al. (2021). Observational application of PPS-calibrated infall times.</li>
        <li id="ref12">Roberts, I. D., et al. (2016). Environmental effects on galaxy star formation.</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="page-tags">
      <strong>Tags:</strong>
      <WikiLink slug="pages/tag_environmental_effects" text="Environmental Effects" />
      <WikiLink slug="pages/tag_quenching_mechanisms" text="Quenching Mechanisms" />
      <WikiLink slug="pages/tag_galaxy_clusters" text="Galaxy Clusters" />
      <WikiLink slug="pages/tag_galaxy_evolution" text="Galaxy Evolution" />
    </div>
  </main>
</Base>
